From bdbea89c2de6dbfe8e7bd950b2495cb07ca419c0 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: prcdslnc13 <prcdslnc13@gmail.com>
Date: Tue, 28 Apr 2026 13:56:45 -0500
Subject: [PATCH] Quiet MCP server stderr by default; gate verbose behind
 CLAW_MCP_VERBOSE
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Patch 0009 switched MCP stdio framing to NDJSON but left
`McpStdioProcess::spawn` inheriting stderr from the parent. That meant
any benign warning the spawned MCP server emitted at startup —
e.g. ONNX Runtime's GPU device-discovery line under WSL2, which the
brain MCP triggers via `fastembed` — landed directly on the user's TTY
the moment claw started.

Pipe MCP stderr instead of inheriting it. A background tokio task
drains the pipe and routes lines to a per-server log file at
`<config_home>/logs/mcp-<server>.stderr` so panics and real errors
remain diagnosable. Set `CLAW_MCP_VERBOSE=1` to restore the old
inherit-stderr behavior for live debugging.

Two env knobs:

- CLAW_MCP_VERBOSE=1   forward stderr to the parent (today's behavior).
- CLAW_MCP_LOG_DISABLED=1   discard stderr instead of writing to disk
  (used by integration tests to avoid leaving empty log files in the
  developer's real ~/.claw/logs/).

Runtime crate's own lib tests skip the log path via cfg!(test).

Tokio's `fs` feature is added to the runtime crate so the drain task
can append asynchronously without blocking the executor.

Refs: carried-forward "Patch 0009 MCP stderr noise" from the
2026-04-28 session checkpoint.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
